06276nam a22007575i 9780824838324DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20142014hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248383247 a10.1515/97808248383242doi  a(DE-B1597)484287  a(OCoLC)881417703  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aSOC0020002bisacsh04a305.89922442231 aSimon, Gregory M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCaged in on the Outside :bMoral Subjectivity, Selfhood, and Islam in Minangkabau, Indonesia /cGregory M. Simon; ed. by Rita Smith Kipp, David P. Chandler. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b1 b&w illustration  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSoutheast Asia: Politics, Meaning, and Memory ;v6500tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. The Village and the Marketplace: the Moral Structure of a Minangkabau City -- t2. Being Minangkabau: Imagining Adat, Islam, and Ethnic Character -- t3. The Awak People: The Moral Aesthetics of Social Unity -- t4. Living with the Devil: Pure Selves and a Corrupting World -- t5. Fashioning the Paribadi: Indirection and Spaces of the Personal -- t6. Being Muslim Subjects: Essential Tensions and the Promise of Transcendence -- tCoda Subjective Tensions, Flourishing, and Multidimensional Selves -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tOther Volumes in the Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCaged in on the Outside is an intimate ethnographic exploration of the ways in which Minangkabau people understand human value. Minangkabau, an Islamic society in Indonesia that is also the largest matrilineal society in the world, has long fascinated anthropologists. Gregory Simon’s book, based on extended ethnographic research in the small city of Bukittinggi, shines new light on Minangkabau social life by delving into people’s interior lives, calling into question many assumptions about Southeast Asian values and the nature of Islamic practice. It offers a deeply human portrait that will engage readers interested in Indonesia, Islam, and psychological anthropology and those concerned with how human beings fashion and reflect on the moral meanings of their lives.Simon focuses on the tension between the values of social integration and individual autonomy—both of which are celebrated in this Islamic trading society. The book explores a series of ethnographic themes, each one illustrating a facet of this tension and its management in contemporary Minangkabau society: the moral structure of the city and its economic life, the nature of Minangkabau ethnic identity, the etiquette of everyday interactions, conceptions of self and its boundaries, hidden spaces of personal identity, and engagements with Islamic traditions. Simon draws on interviews with Minangkabau men and women, demonstrating how individuals engage with cultural forms and refashion them in the process: forms of etiquette are transformed into a series of symbols tattooed on and then erased from a man’s skin; a woman shares a poem expressing an identity rooted in what cannot be directly revealed; a man puzzles over his neglect of Islamic prayers that have the power to bring him happiness.Applying the lessons of the Minangkabau case more broadly to debates on moral life and subjectivity, Simon makes the case that a deep understanding of moral conceptions and practices, including those of Islam, can never be reached simply by delineating their abstract logics or the public messages they send. Instead, we must examine the subtle meanings these conceptions and practices have for the people who live them and how they interact with the enduring tensions of multidimensional human selves. Borrowing a Minangkabau saying, he maintains that whether emerging in moments of suffering or flourishing, moral subjectivity is always complex, organized by ambitions as elusive as being “caged in on the outside.”  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIslamzIndonesiazBukittinggi. 0aMinangkabau (Indonesian people)zIndonesiazBukittinggixEthnic identity. 0aMinangkabau (Indonesian people)zIndonesiazBukittinggixReligion. 0aMinangkabau (Indonesian people)zIndonesiazBukittinggixSocial life and customs. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh1 aChandler, David P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKipp, Rita Smith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2014-2016z978311056413640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082483832440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824838324423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824838324.jpg  a978-3-11-056413-6  UHP eBook Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagec2000d2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK